**Important:** `@tailwindcss/typography` must be in `dependencies`, NOT `devDependencies`. It is needed at build time and some deployment environments skip devDependencies.

## Supabase Schema (CRITICAL ŌĆö project-specific table names)

### Table naming convention (CRITICAL)

Supabase tables must be **project-specific**, prefixed with the automation's slug (derived from the automation display name or ID). This prevents collisions when multiple apps share the same Supabase project.

**Pattern:** `{automation_slug}_sessions` and `{automation_slug}_messages`

The template ships with generic `chat_sessions` / `chat_messages`. When customizing for a specific automation, rename these in both the migration SQL and `lib/supabase.ts`:

```typescript
export const TABLES = {
  sessions: "{automation_slug}_sessions",
  messages: "{automation_slug}_messages",
} as const;
```

All API routes reference `TABLES.sessions` and `TABLES.messages` ŌĆö never hardcode table names directly.

### Schema structure

Tables are defined in `supabase/migrations/00000000000001_chat.sql`:

- **{prefix}_sessions** ŌĆö id, user_id, title, created_at, updated_at
- **{prefix}_messages** ŌĆö id, session_id, role (user/assistant/tool), content, tool_call (jsonb), created_at

RLS is enabled with permissive policies. Cascade delete from sessions to messages.

## Session Auto-Titling (CRITICAL)

Sessions must NOT stay as "New conversation". After the first userŌĆōassistant exchange, use Claude to generate a concise title (max 6 words) from the user's message.

In `app/api/chat/route.ts`, after persisting the assistant response, check if it's the first exchange (message count Ōēż 3). If so, call Claude with a short prompt like:

```
Summarize this conversation in 4-6 words for a sidebar title. No quotes, no punctuation at the end.
```

Update the session title in Supabase with the result. This runs after the main response stream, so it doesn't slow down the chat.

## Streaming (CRITICAL)

Use `anthropic.messages.stream()` ŌĆö NOT `anthropic.messages.create()` ŌĆö for real token-by-token streaming. The `.on("text", callback)` handler sends each token as an SSE event immediately:

The `send()` helper must be **defensive** ŌĆö the client can disconnect mid-stream, causing `controller.enqueue()` to throw inside the `stream.on("text")` callback:

```typescript
let streamClosed = false;
const send = (data: Record<string, unknown>) => {
  if (streamClosed) return;
  try {
    controller.enqueue(encoder.encode(`data: ${JSON.stringify(data)}\n\n`));
  } catch { streamClosed = true; }
};

const stream = anthropic.messages.stream({ model, max_tokens, system, tools, messages });
stream.on("text", (text) => {
  fullResponse += text;
  send({ type: "text", content: text });
});
const finalMessage = await stream.finalMessage();
```

### Tool loop newline separator

When Claude calls tools and then continues with more text, the pre-tool and post-tool text gets concatenated without any break. Add a `\n\n` separator between tool loop iterations:

```typescript
if (iteration > 0 && fullResponse.length > 0) {
  fullResponse += "\n\n";
  send({ type: "text", content: "\n\n" });
}
```

## Persisting Assistant Messages (CRITICAL)

**Always** store the assistant message in Supabase after each turn ŌĆö even when `fullAssistantResponse` is empty (tool-only responses). If you skip the insert when the text is empty, the next turn loads `[user1, user2]` from Supabase (two consecutive user messages), which the Anthropic API rejects with a 400 error.

Store an empty string for tool-only responses ŌĆö do NOT use a literal placeholder like `"(tool-only response)"` because it leaks into the UI when messages are reloaded.

```typescript
await supabaseAdmin.from(TABLES.messages)
  .insert({ session_id: sessionId, role: "assistant", content: fullAssistantResponse || "" });
```

### Consecutive-role merge (safety net)

Before sending loaded messages to Claude, merge any consecutive same-role messages with `\n\n`. This protects against orphaned DB rows from earlier bugs:

```typescript
const merged: Anthropic.MessageParam[] = [];
for (const msg of filtered) {
  const last = merged[merged.length - 1];
  if (last && last.role === msg.role) {
    last.content = last.content + "\n\n" + msg.content;
  } else {
    merged.push(msg);
  }
}
```

## Error Handling (CRITICAL)

### Per-tool error catching

Catch errors from individual tool executions and pass the error as the tool result. This lets Claude explain the failure gracefully instead of aborting the entire stream:

```typescript
let result: string;
try {
  result = await executeTool(block.name, block.input as Record<string, unknown>);
} catch (e) {
  result = `Tool error: ${e instanceof Error ? e.message : "Unknown error"}`;
}
toolResults.push({ type: "tool_result", tool_use_id: block.id, content: result });
```

### Server-side stream errors

Wrap the SSE error send in try-catch (the controller may already be closed) and always log:

```typescript
} catch (err) {
  console.error("[chat] Stream error:", err);
  try { send({ type: "error", content: err.message }); } catch {}
} finally {
  controller.close();
}
```

### Client-side error handling

The SSE reader must handle `"error"` events ŌĆö do NOT silently ignore them. Also surface non-OK HTTP responses and network errors:

```typescript
// SSE event handling
} else if (event.type === "error") {
  setError(event.content ?? "Something went wrong");
}

// Non-OK response
if (!res.ok || !res.body) {
  setError(`Failed to send message (${res.status})`);
  return;
}

// Network errors (in the outer catch)
} catch (err) {
  setError(err instanceof Error ? err.message : "Network error");
}
```

Expose `error: string | null` from `ChatProvider` and render a destructive-styled bubble in the chat page when non-null. Clear the error when the user sends a new message.

### ChatStreamEvent type

The `ChatStreamEvent` type must include ALL event types the server sends: `"text" | "tool_use" | "tool_result" | "done" | "error" | "title"`. Missing `"title"` from the union is a common oversight.

### System prompt caching

Use `null` as the sentinel for "not yet fetched" and check `cachedCode !== null` (not truthiness). An empty `english_code` is a valid cached value. Network failures should NOT be cached ŌĆö leave `cachedCode` as `null` to allow retry on the next request.

